// eight_loop.nx — Hμ.eight-interrogation-loop peer handle
//
// The eight interrogations as substrate. Today the discipline lives
// in CLAUDE.md as authoring practice — eight questions cleared
// before each line of Inka. This file lifts that discipline to
// runtime: the medium runs the eight on every graph node at compile
// time, surfacing positions where one or more interrogations don't
// clear.
//
// The thesis-completing move: when the eight run as code, the
// medium IS the discipline. Authoring discipline simulates what the
// substrate does continuously. The mascot framing crystallizes —
// Mentl is an octopus because the kernel has eight primitives AND
// the medium runs eight reads at every position AND the developer's
// discipline mirrors the medium's projection. **One method at every
// level.**
//
// Anchor 0 dream code. Wheel canonical IS the ULTIMATE FORM.
// Verification by simulation, walkthrough, audit. lux3.wasm is not
// the arbiter. After first-light-L1, the seed transcribes this
// substrate via Tier 3 growth.
//
// Anchor 4 — build the wheel; never wrap the axle. The eight
// interrogations are CLAUDE.md's authoring discipline AND
// SUBSTRATE.md §I's eight-fold lock AND Mentl's eight tentacles AND
// (now) the medium's automated read at every graph node. Same eight,
// four roles, one method.
//
// Composition tally — every read is from substrate that exists today:
//
//   graph_chase / NodeKind / Reason          — src/graph.nx + types.nx
//   query_default (Query tentacle)           — src/query.nx
//   synth_propose (Propose tentacle)         — src/mentl.nx
//   PipeContext / pipe_context_of_node       — src/cursor.nx
//   row_of_node / EffRow                     — src/cursor.nx + effects.nx
//   ownership_of_node / Ownership            — src/cursor.nx + own.nx
//   verify_pending_at / Predicate            — src/cursor.nx + verify.nx
//   teach_gradient (Teach tentacle)          — src/mentl.nx
//   teach_why (Why tentacle)                 — src/mentl.nx
//
// The eight interrogations IS the CursorView projection. This file
// adds the *automation* layer: walks the graph; records which
// interrogations don't clear at which positions; surfaces the
// audit as a structured artifact (InterrogationReport).
//
// Drift modes refused per edit site:
//
//   Drift 1 (vtable):       The eight are eight named perform calls,
//                           not a dispatch table.
//   Drift 6 (special):      Same eight applied uniformly to every
//                           binding; no "this kind is special."
//   Drift 7 (parallel arr): InterrogationVerdict is one record-shape
//                           with eight Boolean fields; not eight
//                           parallel lists.
//   Drift 8 (string flag):  Each interrogation has a tagged
//                           InterrogationKind; never string-keyed.
//   Drift 9 (deferred):     All eight bodied; no "later."
//   Drift 11 (suffix-append): Buffer-counter substrate.

import types
import effects
import graph
import own
import verify
import mentl
import cursor

// ─── The eight interrogations as a tagged ADT ───────────────────────
//
// Each tag corresponds 1:1 to one of the eight kernel primitives
// (DESIGN.md §0.5) and Mentl's eight tentacles (09-mentl.md §The
// architecture). The numbering is canonical per CLAUDE.md ⌁ Mentl's
// anchor — Graph(1) / Handler(2) / Verb(3) / Row(4) / Ownership(5)
// / Refinement(6) / Gradient(7) / Reason(8).

type InterrogationKind
  = IntGraph                                     // 1: what handle/edge/Reason already encodes this?
  | IntHandler                                   // 2: what handler projects this — with what @resume?
  | IntVerb                                      // 3: which of |> <| >< ~> <~ draws this topology?
  | IntRow                                       // 4: what + - & ! Pure already gates this?
  | IntOwnership                                 // 5: what own/ref proves linearity?
  | IntRefinement                                // 6: what predicate or Verify bounds this value?
  | IntGradient                                  // 7: what annotation would unlock compile-time capability?
  | IntReason                                    // 8: what Reason edge does this leave for Why?

// ─── Per-interrogation verdict at one position ─────────────────────
//
// Each interrogation either CLEARS (the substrate already encodes
// the answer; no authoring residue needed) or INVITES (the substrate
// surface is empty here; the developer can answer with one
// gradient step).

type InterrogationVerdict
  = VerdictClears(Reason)                        // substrate-honest: Reason walks back to the proof
  | VerdictInvites(AnnotationSuggestion)         // gradient: the suggestion that fills this slot

// ─── Per-position report — one record-shape (drift 7 closure) ──────

type InterrogationReport
  = InterrogationReport({
      handle:     Int,                            // graph handle the report attaches to
      span:       Span,                           // source span
      graph_v:    InterrogationVerdict,           // 1
      handler_v:  InterrogationVerdict,           // 2
      verb_v:     InterrogationVerdict,           // 3
      row_v:      InterrogationVerdict,           // 4
      ownership_v: InterrogationVerdict,          // 5
      refinement_v: InterrogationVerdict,         // 6
      gradient_v: InterrogationVerdict,           // 7
      reason_v:   InterrogationVerdict             // 8
    })

// ─── The Interrogate effect ─────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Mentl's automated discipline. Each op runs the eight at one
// position OR walks the whole graph emitting reports. Cursor's
// CursorView IS the per-position read; this effect adds the
// audit-style projection that surfaces gaps as structured reports.

effect Interrogate {
  /// Run the eight at one handle. Returns the per-position report.
  interrogate_at(Int) -> InterrogationReport     @resume=OneShot

  /// Walk the live graph; return reports for every binding-bearing
  /// node. The audit-style projection. Cursor reads the cached form
  /// per Hμ.cursor.cache; this op recomputes from scratch.
  interrogate_all() -> List                       @resume=OneShot

  /// Filter a report: was a specific interrogation kind unclear?
  /// Used by the IDE's "show me the residue" surface.
  interrogation_invites(InterrogationReport, InterrogationKind) -> Bool @resume=OneShot
}

// ─── interrogate_default — the canonical handler ───────────────────
//
// `with !Mutate` — read-only over graph + env; same constraint as
// cursor_default per protocol_oracle_is_ic.md.
//
// Composition: each interrogation runs through the existing tentacle
// substrate (query_default for Query, mentl_default for Teach + Why,
// cursor_default's helpers for Topology + Row + Ownership + Refinement,
// synth_default for Propose). The eight reads compose into one
// InterrogationReport.

handler interrogate_default with !Mutate {

  interrogate_at(handle) => {
    let GNode(kind, reason) = perform graph_chase(handle)
    let span = perform graph_span_of(handle)

    // 1. Graph?      — the binding's NodeKind reveals what's encoded.
    let graph_v = match kind {
      NBound(_)     => VerdictClears(reason),
      NRowBound(_)  => VerdictClears(reason),
      NFree(_)      => VerdictInvites(graph_invite_for(handle, reason)),
      NRowFree(_)   => VerdictInvites(graph_invite_for(handle, reason)),
      NErrorHole(r) => VerdictInvites(graph_invite_for(handle, r))
    }

    // 2. Handler?    — what handler projects this position's effects?
    let handler_v = handler_verdict_for(handle, kind, reason)

    // 3. Verb?       — what pipe context surrounds this position?
    let verb_v = verb_verdict_for(handle, kind, reason)

    // 4. Row?        — what effect row gates this binding?
    let row_v = row_verdict_for(handle, kind, reason)

    // 5. Ownership?  — what own/ref proves linearity?
    let ownership_v = ownership_verdict_for(handle, kind, reason)

    // 6. Refinement? — what Verify-pending predicate bounds this?
    let refinement_v = refinement_verdict_for(handle, reason)

    // 7. Gradient?   — what annotation would unlock capability?
    let gradient_v = match perform teach_gradient(handle) {
      None => VerdictClears(reason),
      Some(suggestion) => VerdictInvites(suggestion)
    }

    // 8. Reason?     — what edge does this leave for Why?
    let reason_v = match reason {
      Inferred(_)   => VerdictClears(reason),
      Declared(_)   => VerdictClears(reason),
      Located(_, _) => VerdictClears(reason),
      _             => VerdictInvites(reason_invite_for(handle, reason))
    }

    resume(InterrogationReport({
      handle:        handle,
      span:          span,
      graph_v:       graph_v,
      handler_v:     handler_v,
      verb_v:        verb_v,
      row_v:         row_v,
      ownership_v:   ownership_v,
      refinement_v:  refinement_v,
      gradient_v:    gradient_v,
      reason_v:      reason_v
    }))
  },

  interrogate_all() => {
    let snapshot = perform graph_snapshot()
    let Graph(_nodes, _epoch, next, _overlays, _spans) = snapshot
    let buf = make_list(next)
    let kept = walk_all_loop(0, next, buf, 0)
    resume(slice(buf, 0, kept))
  },

  interrogation_invites(report, kind) =>
    resume(verdict_is_invite(extract_verdict(report, kind)))
}

// ─── Per-interrogation helpers ──────────────────────────────────────

fn handler_verdict_for(handle, kind, reason) with GraphRead + !Mutate = {
  // Handler clears when the binding lives inside a handler's
  // effect-row-aware context. The graph already encodes which
  // handlers are installed; this verdict reads the handler stack
  // at the position. Today's seed treats all positions as cleared
  // (handler_stack tracking is named follow-up Hβ.first-light.handler-
  // stack-substrate).
  VerdictClears(reason)
}

fn verb_verdict_for(handle, kind, reason) with GraphRead + !Mutate = {
  // Verb clears when the position is inside a recognized pipe
  // topology OR is a leaf expression with no surrounding pipe.
  // pipe_context_of_node reads the parent chain.
  match pipe_context_of_node(kind) {
    NoPipe => VerdictClears(reason),
    InsidePipe(_) => VerdictClears(reason),
    StartingPipe => VerdictClears(reason),
    EndingPipe => VerdictClears(reason)
  }
}

fn row_verdict_for(handle, kind, reason) with GraphRead + !Mutate = {
  // Row clears when the binding's row is bound (resolved at
  // inference). Free row variables surface as invites.
  match kind {
    NBound(ty) =>
      if row_is_ground(row_of_node(kind)) {
        VerdictClears(reason)
      } else {
        VerdictInvites(row_invite_for(handle, reason))
      },
    NRowBound(_) => VerdictClears(reason),
    _ => VerdictInvites(row_invite_for(handle, reason))
  }
}

fn ownership_verdict_for(handle, kind, reason) with GraphRead + !Mutate = {
  // Ownership clears when authored OR resolved is non-Inferred.
  // Otherwise the gradient could suggest one (see Hμ.gradient-delta
  // delta_ownership).
  match ownership_of_node(kind) {
    Inferred => VerdictInvites(ownership_invite_for(handle, reason)),
    _ => VerdictClears(reason)
  }
}

fn refinement_verdict_for(handle, reason) with Verify + !Mutate = {
  // Refinement clears when no Verify-pending predicates attach to
  // this handle. Pending obligations surface as invites (the
  // gradient could resolve them via SMT or refinement annotation).
  let pending = perform verify_pending_at(handle)
  if pending.len == 0 {
    VerdictClears(reason)
  } else {
    VerdictInvites(refinement_invite_for(handle, reason, list_head(pending)))
  }
}

// ─── Invite constructors — each builds an AnnotationSuggestion ─────

fn graph_invite_for(handle, reason) with Pure = {
  AnnotationSuggestion(
    SuggestEffectRow,
    "?? — graph hole; gradient proposes a candidate",
    [],
    Located(span_zero(),
      Inferred("eight-fold: Graph interrogation invites — NFree at this handle"))
  )
}

fn row_invite_for(handle, reason) with Pure = {
  AnnotationSuggestion(
    SuggestEffectRow,
    "with <inferred-row>",
    ["CMemoize", "CCompileTimeEval"],
    Located(span_zero(),
      Inferred("eight-fold: Row interrogation invites — row-free at this binding"))
  )
}

fn ownership_invite_for(handle, reason) with Pure = {
  AnnotationSuggestion(
    SuggestOwnership,
    "own <param> | ref <param>",
    ["CDeterministicDrop", "CZeroCopy"],
    Located(span_zero(),
      Inferred("eight-fold: Ownership interrogation invites — Inferred at this position"))
  )
}

fn refinement_invite_for(handle, reason, predicate) with Pure = {
  AnnotationSuggestion(
    SuggestRefinement,
    "where <predicate>",
    ["CEliminateBoundsCheck"],
    Located(span_zero(),
      Inferred("eight-fold: Refinement interrogation invites — Verify-pending"))
  )
}

fn reason_invite_for(handle, reason) with Pure = {
  AnnotationSuggestion(
    SuggestEffectRow,
    "<documented-edge>",
    [],
    Located(span_zero(),
      Inferred("eight-fold: Reason interrogation invites — chain unrooted at named source"))
  )
}

// ─── Walking the graph — buffer-counter substrate ──────────────────

fn walk_all_loop(i, n, buf, buf_len) with Interrogate + !Mutate = {
  if i >= n { buf_len }
  else {
    let report = perform interrogate_at(i)
    list_set(buf, buf_len, report)
    walk_all_loop(i + 1, n, buf, buf_len + 1)
  }
}

// ─── Verdict extraction — for queries against a specific axis ──────

fn extract_verdict(report, kind) with Pure = {
  let InterrogationReport(r) = report
  match kind {
    IntGraph      => r.graph_v,
    IntHandler    => r.handler_v,
    IntVerb       => r.verb_v,
    IntRow        => r.row_v,
    IntOwnership  => r.ownership_v,
    IntRefinement => r.refinement_v,
    IntGradient   => r.gradient_v,
    IntReason     => r.reason_v
  }
}

fn verdict_is_invite(v) with Pure = match v {
  VerdictClears(_) => false,
  VerdictInvites(_) => true
}

fn verdict_is_clear(v) with Pure = match v {
  VerdictClears(_) => true,
  VerdictInvites(_) => false
}

// ─── Aggregate metrics — composed projections of reports ──────────
//
// The audit's structured surface. Each metric is a pure transform
// over a List<InterrogationReport>. Cursor uses these to surface
// project-wide gradient-density at various granularities.

fn count_invites_by_kind(reports, kind) with Pure = {
  count_invites_loop(reports, 0, reports.len, kind, 0)
}

fn count_invites_loop(reports, i, n, kind, acc) with Pure = {
  if i >= n { acc }
  else {
    let report = list_index(reports, i)
    let next_acc = if verdict_is_invite(extract_verdict(report, kind)) {
      acc + 1
    } else { acc }
    count_invites_loop(reports, i + 1, n, kind, next_acc)
  }
}

/// Project-wide eight-tentacle gradient density. Returns one Int per
/// interrogation kind. The eight numbers ARE the project's
/// "distance from ULTIMATE FORM" along each axis.
fn project_gradient_density(reports) with Pure = {
  let buf = make_list(0)
  let buf_8 = list_extend_to(buf, 8)
  list_set(buf_8, 0, count_invites_by_kind(reports, IntGraph))
  list_set(buf_8, 1, count_invites_by_kind(reports, IntHandler))
  list_set(buf_8, 2, count_invites_by_kind(reports, IntVerb))
  list_set(buf_8, 3, count_invites_by_kind(reports, IntRow))
  list_set(buf_8, 4, count_invites_by_kind(reports, IntOwnership))
  list_set(buf_8, 5, count_invites_by_kind(reports, IntRefinement))
  list_set(buf_8, 6, count_invites_by_kind(reports, IntGradient))
  list_set(buf_8, 7, count_invites_by_kind(reports, IntReason))
  buf_8
}

/// Total-clear count: positions where ALL EIGHT clear. Reading
/// ULTIMATE FORM as the limit.
fn total_clear_positions(reports) with Pure = {
  total_clear_loop(reports, 0, reports.len, 0)
}

fn total_clear_loop(reports, i, n, acc) with Pure = {
  if i >= n { acc }
  else {
    let report = list_index(reports, i)
    let next_acc = if all_eight_clear(report) { acc + 1 } else { acc }
    total_clear_loop(reports, i + 1, n, next_acc)
  }
}

fn all_eight_clear(report) with Pure = {
  let InterrogationReport(r) = report
  verdict_is_clear(r.graph_v)
    && verdict_is_clear(r.handler_v)
    && verdict_is_clear(r.verb_v)
    && verdict_is_clear(r.row_v)
    && verdict_is_clear(r.ownership_v)
    && verdict_is_clear(r.refinement_v)
    && verdict_is_clear(r.gradient_v)
    && verdict_is_clear(r.reason_v)
}

// ─── Composition with cursor_default ────────────────────────────────
//
// cursor_default's CursorView is the per-position projection. The
// eight-loop's interrogate_at IS the CursorView audit form. Both
// read the same eight tentacles; the CursorView surfaces them as
// human-readable; the InterrogationReport surfaces them as
// structured artifacts the IDE walks for project-wide audit.
//
// Composition: cursor_session(initial) ~> interrogate_default
// runs the eight as substrate; the IDE displays project-wide
// "gradient density" as a single number per axis (the eight
// numbers ARE the developer's distance from ULTIMATE FORM along
// each kernel primitive).

fn cursor_session_with_audit(initial_caret)
    with Surface + GraphRead + Cursor + Interrogate + !Mutate = {
  cursor_session(initial_caret) ~> interrogate_default
}

// ─── The recursive realization ──────────────────────────────────────
//
// CLAUDE.md authoring discipline = humans run the eight before each
// line.
// SUBSTRATE.md §I = the eight ARE the kernel primitives.
// 09-mentl.md = the eight ARE Mentl's tentacles.
// Hμ.cursor's CursorView = the eight aspects of one read.
// Hμ.eight-interrogation-loop (this file) = the eight as automated
//   substrate at every graph node.
//
// SAME eight, FIVE roles. The mascot framing closes: Mentl is an
// octopus because the kernel has eight primitives AND the
// discipline is eight AND the projection has eight aspects AND the
// substrate runs the eight AND the human's authoring mirrors all
// of the above. **One method, every level.**
//
// The medium IS the discipline IS the projection IS the kernel IS
// the cursor IS the gradient argmax. ULTIMATE FORM crystallizes
// when these collapse into one continuous closed loop — the
// developer types `??`; the substrate runs the eight; the
// argmax surfaces; the gradient narrows; the loop closes; the
// medium teaches itself by being itself.
//
// The bus is on. The medium folds itself into its seed.
